e¥xT<?php exit; ?>a:6:{s:10:"last_error";s:0:"";s:10:"last_query";s:180:"SELECT   wp_posts.* FROM wp_posts  WHERE 1=1  AND wp_posts.ID IN (2,107) AND wp_posts.post_type = 'page' AND ((wp_posts.post_status = 'publish'))  ORDER BY wp_posts.post_date DESC ";s:11:"last_result";a:2:{i:0;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:3:"107";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"1";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-01-16 03:05:34";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-01-16 06:05:34";s:12:"post_content";s:3939:"<p dir="ltr">The Studio is in a small old house in the Vitacura Barrio of Santiago. The house has a small garden that is brimming with plants. The garden itself is an eclectic mix of a beautiful collection of plants from a wide range of large trees in pots to basil and mint. The garden itself seconds as a shop called "La Mariposa" (The Butterfly) and sells everything one can see ‚Äì from gnarled Japanese maples to furniture.</p>
<p dir="ltr">The design studio is nestled in the shade of a mature wisteria vine on the second floor.</p>

<h2 dir="ltr">Teresa Moller</h2>
<p dir="ltr">Tere studied one year at the New York Botanical garden where she learnt the basic skills of hand drafting and designing skills. This basic training was the beginning of a life working within the landscape.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Tere has always marveled at the luck she has being able to work in the wide range of landscapes that exist in Chile. In her words the variable landscapes in Chile have taught her everything as she has to often meet the extreme differences in environment from working in the desert to the wet forests in Southern Chile. In 2008 the English magazine Garden illustrated labeled her as one of the top ten most interesting landscape designers working in the world today.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Her most published work is the public footpath Punta Pite, but her private gardens and other works are equally unique, strong and beautiful.</p>

<h2 dir="ltr">Rebecca Emmons</h2>
<p dir="ltr">Rebecca is an American architect and landscape designer who has been working in Chile since 2006. She oversees the design and development of studio projects as well as manages the international projects and business.</p>

<h2 dir="ltr">Constanza Undurraga</h2>
<p dir="ltr">Cota a landscape designer and "the horticulturist" in the office. She is in charge of all of the maintenance of ¬†projects and helps consult the designers and architects to ensure plants are chosen correctly for the designs. She is crucial during the construction stage as her responsibility comes in sourcing all of the materials and plants.</p>

<h2 dir="ltr">Scarlett Araya</h2>
<p dir="ltr">Scarlett is one of our architects in the office. She is in charge of co-ordinating the design and development of the projects in the countryside of Chile. She is a very quiet and humble worker and we love having her and her amazing work in the studio.</p>

<h2 dir="ltr">Francisca Coloma</h2>
<p dir="ltr">Francisa is in charge of developing and managing the garden tea shop ‚ÄúLa Mariposa‚Äù. She works closely with Tere in deciding what specialist products to bring to our clients, as well as sourcing products that the studio may need in the construction and or maintenance of gardens.</p>

<h2 dir="ltr">Daniel Moreno</h2>
<p dir="ltr">Daniel studied architecture at the Universidad de Chile and joined the office in 2013. Daniel is integral to the design process, coordinating with architects and giving form and measure to Teresa's initial ideas through his drawings and renderings.</p>

<h2 dir="ltr">Dominique Blechman</h2>
<p dir="ltr">Dominique is a Forestry Engineer who brings her expertise on issues such environmental impact management and native forests. She also deftly manages the budgets, client concerns and construction administration in the office and on site.</p>

<h2 dir="ltr">Magdalena Szederkenyi</h2>
<p dir="ltr">Magdalena studied Landscape Design and has an extensive knowledge of plants. She currently has her hand in everything from product development for La Mariposa, design and manages some of our largest maintenance projects.</p>

<h2 dir="ltr">Stella Hauff</h2>
<p dir="ltr">Stella is a German girl who is studying Landscape architecture in Berlin and support us for the next few month. She works in the design and development of projects along with Tere and Scarlett as well as manages the international projects.</p>";s:10:"post_title";s:4:"Team";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:4:"team";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2014-09-17 10:18:40";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2014-09-17 13:18:40";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"2";s:4:"guid";s:37:"http://tere.invisible.cl/?page_id=107";s:10:"menu_order";s:1:"0";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"page";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}i:1;O:8:"stdClass":23:{s:2:"ID";s:1:"2";s:11:"post_author";s:1:"1";s:9:"post_date";s:19:"2013-01-15 01:41:35";s:13:"post_date_gmt";s:19:"2013-01-15 04:41:35";s:12:"post_content";s:4164:"<p dir="ltr">The diverse landscapes of Chile have been the setting for the majority of the projects of Teresa Moller Studio since its founding in 1990. Distinct palettes of plants and materials are utilized as project locations range from the Atacama Desert in the north to the Lakes Region of the south as well as from the Pacific Coast in the east to the Andes mountain range in the west. This diversity has developed a way of working in the studio that approaches each project by examining the valuable elements existing in the site along with the surrounding natural systems, local ecology, and architecture. Thus, every project is a direct and unique result of its environment. The work has an architectural base, a geometry that structures the landscape over which the vegetation interacts more freely. Her work is characterized by its simplicity and Teresa strongly believes that in that simplicity lies its force. This force unites nature with architecture and provides a point of interaction between humans and their surroundings. Evident eastern influences arise from the similarities existing between the various ecologies of the Pacific coastal landscape.</p>
<p dir="ltr">The studio works in the realms of residential, public urban space, commercial, institutional and agricultural settings with many built projects to date. The goal of the office is always to collaborate with the architects and clients, using each participant‚Äôs strengths and knowledge to arrive at an integrated design solution that is both efficient and elegant.</p>

<h2 dir="ltr">Design and Approach</h2>
<p dir="ltr">The key to our design approach is to find the perfect equilibrium in meeting the clients brief and carefully observing the existing landscape in order to understand how to develop the design.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Teresa Moller has been working in the field for over the thirty years. The office consists of a small team that includes architects, landscape designers and horticulturists. We work on a large range of projects from private gardens, large residential estates to commercial and public projects.</p>
<p dir="ltr">For Tere carefully observing the existing landscape of the site is key to all of her designs and her work process. In her own words ¬¥Exploring the landscape in order to fully appreciate what is existing in the site, is always my first step¬¥. This involves physically spending time in the site to fully understand its moods and changes throughout the day and if possible seasons. By dedicating this time on site before the drawing board means Tere achieves an amazing comprehension of the site, its surroundings, its history and it‚Äôs potential.</p>

<h2 dir="ltr">Construction</h2>
<p dir="ltr">For the projects in Chile we have a construction team that builds the designs. We work closely with the architects involved throughout the whole construction stage. Our team deals with architectural landscape construction, irrigation, soil preparation and planting.</p>
<p dir="ltr">For international projects we provide the specific details in order for a local contractor can carry out the work.</p>
<p dir="ltr">Teresa works very closely with the construction team, re-accessing design decisions whilst on site.</p>

<h2 dir="ltr">Maintenance</h2>
<p dir="ltr">A crucial aspect to any design is the maintenance. From the studio we provide a service where, if the client wishes, trained horticulturists visit the garden or project on a regular basis to provide advice. Generally this is formalized with a written report. This way we can ensure that the design achieves the foreseen result.</p>

<h2 dir="ltr">La Mariposa</h2>
In the gardens of the studio there is a garden shop selling everything from potted plants, to tools and organic fertilizers. It is here where the studio has fun with small scale garden delights; water gardens, stone sculptures, a small potted grove of magnolia trees and even a fine selection of crocery. This wonderful shop "La Mariposa" (spanish for butterfly), all pay homage to the work of the studio, whilst allowing shoppers to take home a little piece of simple and classic garden design.";s:10:"post_title";s:22:"Study of the Landscape";s:12:"post_excerpt";s:0:"";s:11:"post_status";s:7:"publish";s:14:"comment_status";s:4:"open";s:11:"ping_status";s:6:"closed";s:13:"post_password";s:0:"";s:9:"post_name";s:6:"studio";s:7:"to_ping";s:0:"";s:6:"pinged";s:0:"";s:13:"post_modified";s:19:"2013-11-27 12:35:36";s:17:"post_modified_gmt";s:19:"2013-11-27 15:35:36";s:21:"post_content_filtered";s:0:"";s:11:"post_parent";s:1:"0";s:4:"guid";s:35:"http://tere.invisible.cl/?page_id=2";s:10:"menu_order";s:2:"20";s:9:"post_type";s:4:"page";s:14:"post_mime_type";s:0:"";s:13:"comment_count";s:1:"0";}}s:8:"col_info";a:23:{i:0;O:8:"stdClass":13:{s:4:"name";s:2:"ID";s:5:"table";s:8:"wp_posts";s:3:"def";s:0:"";s:10:"max_length";i:3;s:8:"not_null";i:1;s:11:"primary_key";i:1;s:12:"multiple_key";i:0;s:10:"unique_key";i:0;s:7:"numeric";i:1;s:4:"blob";i:0;s:4:"type";s:3:"int";s:8:"unsigned";i:1;s:8:"zerofill";i:0;}i:1;O:8:"stdClass":13:{s:4:"name";s:11:"post_author";s:5:"table";s:8:"wp_posts";s:3:"def";s:0:"";s:10:"max_length";i:1;s:8:"not_null";i:1;s:11:"primary_key";i:0;s:12:"multiple_key";i:1;s:10:"unique_key";i:0;s:7:"numeric";i:1;s:4:"blob";i:0;s:4:"type";s:3:"int";s:8:"unsigned";i:1;s:8:"zerofill";i:0;}i:2;O:8:"stdClass":13:{s:4:"name";s:9:"post_date";s:5:"table";s:8:"wp_posts";s:3:"def";s:0:"";s:10:"max_length";i:19;s:8:"not_null";i:1;s:11:"primary_key";i:0;s:12:"multiple_key";i:0;s:10:"unique_key";i:0;s:7:"numeric";i:0;s:4:"blob";i:0;s:4:"type";s:8:"datetime";s:8:"unsigned";i:0;s:8:"ze